I found two sources of property data for my local county. Each dataset contains fields that are similar and some that are not, if there are enough similar fields I can create a key using the most minimal number of fields for each parcel and then compare the data collected in each data set. Luckily for me parcels of land have ids, addresses and owners and each of these tables have those fields, they are just formatted differently. Once I have identified unique parcels I can begin comparing fields that are MEANT to contain the same data for that parcel.

df1 has one column for owner, df2 has columns for each part of the name of each owner. I like the idea of one column for owner name becuase I would like to use this column as a key for all of the data. So I will make a column in df2 that combines the columns of names. df1 also appears to have parcel ids that are not in the same format as df2 so I will change it to df2's format.

Below is a quick stradegy I created to compare fields to determine if they have similar data(not just the same data type). I use a list of all possible pairs of columns and find all of the unique elements in each. The value calculated is the ratio of intersection to the total number of elements in each list. I then scale this by two so that 1 is a perfect score.

This method will only suggest columns that have the same data, but it can easily be misleading. If two columns were categorical in nature encoded with integers or had the same data but representing different topics. Then it will show a good score, the method is only supposed to suggest similar data, not recommend that they do in fact represent the SAME data. However, when two columns appear to have the same data and they have column names that suggest the same source of the data then it may mean that the two columns are suppose to measure the same data.

A good example for these datasets would be TaxValue in df1 vesus taxable_val in df2 or FireDistri in df1 versus fire_code in df2. You could go through each column and with enough subject matter speaicality decide if two columns measure the same data, but if you are not a SME, like myself it helps to have a program suggest like columns.

In [10]:
pairs = [[x,y] for x in df1.columns for y in df2.columns]

t = PrettyTable(['Columns', 'Percent','Size of Intersection'])

for pair in tqdm(pairs, mininterval = 0.5, ascii = False):
    a = df1[pair[0]].unique()
    b = df2[pair[1]].unique()
    inter = set(a).intersection(set(b))

    value = 2*len(inter)/(len(a)+len(b))

    if value > 0.6:
        t.add_row([pair, round(value,2), len(inter)])
    else:
        pass
    
t.sortby = "Percent"
t.reversesort = True
print(t)

By plotting similar columns against one another we can tell right away the severity of any discrepancies. We would expect that if two columns represent the same data then plotting one against the other should produce the line y = x. What we see below is that in df1 parcels were most likely given a 0 value when the information was not known, if we trusted df2 then we could actually fill in these missing values. For my purposes though I will discredit these instances since I already have so many parcels to work with.

#function to compare columns of same type
def comp_2(clist, df, error):
    x, y = clist[0], clist[1]
    try:
        out = df[abs(df[x] - df[y]) > error]
    except:
        out = df[df[x] != df[y]]
        
    print('DF size:',len(df) ,'/Count One: ',df[x].count(),'/Count Two: ',df[y].count() ,'/Count Discrepancies: ',len(out[[x,y]]))
    
    return list(out[[x,y]].index)

Now what I want to do is get rid of columns with duplicate data. Since I have filtered the data to only show parcels that were in strict agreement with parcel id, owner, tax value, land value, building value, acres and street name I am confident in dropping the df1 df2 nomenclature and I will use these fields for subsequent analysis. The next step I would like to take is geocoding the addresses so that information on each parcel can be translated into data that is location dependent and I can make pretty graphs! So the following loop makes requests to the US Census geocoding api. It will not be able to find all longitude and latitude for each parcel so that will filter the data even more.

In [31]:
result = result[0:100]
lat = []
lon = []
for index, row in tqdm(result.iterrows(), total=result.shape[0]):
    address = row.address
    try:
        r = requests.get('https://geocoding.geo.census.gov/geocoder/locations/onelineaddress?address=' + address +'&benchmark=Public_AR_Census2010&format=json')
        coord = r.json()['result']['addressMatches'][0]['coordinates']
        lon.append(coord['x'])
        lat.append(coord['y'])
    except:
        lat.append(None)
        lon.append(None) 

result['lat'] = lat
result['lon'] = lon
result = result.dropna(subset = ['lat','lon'])

#Below is a quick method for find the density of parcels with column values above or below the mean
def kde_col_plot(column):
    mean = data[column].mean()
    g1 = sns.jointplot(x="lon", y="lat", data=data[data[column] >= mean], kind="kde", color="g")
    g2 = sns.jointplot(x="lon", y="lat", data=data[data[column] <= mean], kind="kde", color="r")

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    gs = gridspec.GridSpec(1, 2)

    mg1 = SeabornFig2Grid(g1, fig, gs[0])
    mg2 = SeabornFig2Grid(g2, fig, gs[1])

    gs.tight_layout(fig)
    #gs.update(top=0.7)

    return plt.show()

These kde plots can be useful when we pass a filtered data frame so we can look at the density of parcels that meet any criteria we wish based on the information we have. The plots below show the density of parcels when values above (green) and below (red) there respective means. For example when looking at the kde plots for acres you can tell that there is a peak in the center for parcels that are below the mean I believe that this is because a lot of the small parcels are at the center of the city.
